{
  "translated_title": "[Culture Briefs] 'Korean Language Society Literary Lecture' and Others",
  "translated_text": "■ The Korean Language Society will hold a literary lecture on the 22nd at 2 PM at Nanjeongdang on the 8th floor of the Korean Language Society Building in Seocho-dong, Seocho-gu, Seoul, with the theme 'Practical Use and Educational Methods of Chinese Characters,' discussing the utilization of Chinese characters in daily life, Korean pronunciation methods, and Chinese character education methods. Middle and high school frontline teachers and hagwon instructors will present on topics such as 'Middle School Chinese Character Class Methods,' 'Current Status and Direction of High School Chinese Character Education,' and 'Characteristics of Chinese Character Education by Age Group.' Additionally, former KBS announcer Lee Gyu-hang will speak about the pronunciation of Sino-Korean words. 02-6003-1405\n■ The humanities research group 'Research Space Suyu+Neomeo' and joint reading club '100books Club' will hold invited lectures and discussion sessions on the 22nd and 23rd at 'Onjidang' in Deokmyeong-dong, Yuseong-gu, Daejeon [a city south of Seoul], with the theme 'Encounter Between Natural Sciences and Humanities.' After lectures by Professor Choi Jae-cheon, chair professor in the Department of Natural Sciences at Ewha Womans University, and Professor Emeritus Lee Jong-sang from Seoul National University's College of Fine Arts on interdisciplinary convergence, various topics will be presented including 'Korean Literature After the IMF [Crisis],' 'Buddhism and Buddhist Studies,' 'Communism and Singularity,' 'Immune System and Self,' 'Meeting of Engineering and Management,' and 'Brain and Creativity.' (www.100booksclub.com)\n■ Inha University's Korean Studies Research Institute will hold an academic conference on the 20th at 2 PM in the main conference room of Inha University's Jeongseok Academic Information Center with the theme 'Modern Buddhism and East Asia.' Presentations and discussions will be conducted on subtopics such as 'Modern Significance of the No-Self Ethics Proposed by Zhang Taiyan,' 'Relationship Between Buddhism and Modern Literature in Japan,' 'Penetration of Modern Japanese Buddhist Forces and Trends in the Buddhist Community,' and 'Buddhist Perception in North Korea, Focusing on the Evaluation of Manhae Han Yong-un.' 032-860-8268"
}

{
  "translated_title": "[Reader's Letter] Lee Seon-hwa/High School Sophomore Korean, English, and Math for Elementary Students...",
  "translated_text": "Recently, while visiting several hagwons to transfer my 6th-grade child to a new one, I received a shocking proposal at one hagwon. They recommended enrolling my child in their specialized high school prep class. The admissions counselor told me that the 6th-grade elementary students currently attending that hagwon are learning combinations and permutations in math. She said combinations and permutations are part of the high school sophomore curriculum. She added that not only math, but English is also taught directly by native speakers, and Korean essay-writing is also at high school level. The cost was 2.5 million won [approximately $1,900 USD] for just four subjects: math, science, English, and Korean. I was speechless and just left.

There's a fever for specialized high schools because people think getting into one makes admission to prestigious universities easier. As a result, this kind of hagwon education seems to have emerged based on the calculation that students must complete the high school freshman curriculum by 6th grade at the latest to have a shot at specialized high schools. I question whether having even elementary students fight the specialized high school admissions war is truly sound education policy.

Lee Seon-hwa, Junggye 1-dong, Nowon-gu, Seoul"
}

{
  "translated_title": "[Rambling Thoughts/Hong Chan-sik] The Revival of Philosophy",
  "translated_text": "Philosophy courses, which had been shunned by American college students, are reportedly gaining popularity again. According to a New York Times report on the 6th, at the City University of New York, the number of philosophy majors has reached 322 students, a 50% increase from six years ago. When analyzing LSAT (Law School Admission Test) scores taken by American law school applicants, students who majored in philosophy as undergraduates had the second-highest average scores overall. First place went to physics majors.\n▷The LSAT is the representative test for measuring logical and analytical thinking abilities in the United States. This newly confirms the fact that studying philosophy is perfectly suited for developing such capabilities. American college students favor studying philosophy not only for the practical reason that it's advantageous for law school admission, but also as a 'compass' to navigate an uncertain future. The 'Top Leader Humanities Program' established by Seoul National University's College of Liberal Arts last year achieved unexpected success for the same reason. The CEOs who enrolled in this program said they gained management wisdom by attending lectures on Kant's Critique of Pure Reason.\n▷The 'revival of philosophy' movement is also being detected in Korea's university admissions. This year's admissions saw rising competition rates for philosophy departments at top-tier universities. University officials point out that this is not unrelated to the opening of law schools in March next year. With the opening of law schools, law departments will disappear, and in this case, many students think that majoring in philosophy would be advantageous for law school admission after graduation. Whatever the reason, this is a welcome development.\n▷At the end of July, the 22nd World Philosophy Congress, called the 'Philosophy Olympics,' will be held in Seoul. Established in 1900 and previously held only in European cultural regions, this is the first time the congress is being held in a non-European region. The theme is 'Rethinking Philosophy Today.' Philosophy is the 'classic of learning' containing humanity's long-standing wisdom, but today it faces a crisis to the extent that it 'must be rethought.' However, strictly speaking, philosophy has always been in the same place—perhaps modern people, swept up by trends, simply failed to recognize its true value. Philosophy's vitality will be eternal as long as humans don't give up being 'thinking animals.' I hope that Korea, using the World Philosophy Congress as an opportunity, will become a cultural hub leading the way in 'reconsidering philosophy.'"
}

